3. Invoking JavaScript Functions

- A JavaScript function runs when it is called.
- To call a function, write the name followed by parentheses like name().

#) Function Invocation:
    - The code inside a function will execute when "something" invokes the function:
        -> When it is called from JavaScript code
        -> When an event occurs (a user clicks a button)
        -> Automatically (self invoked)
    
    - The code below invokes the function. But it does not use the result.

            <script>
                function sayHello() {
                    return "Hello User";
                }
                sayHello();
            </script>

        -> expected result is  'Hello user' but you'll get nothing because the returned result is
            not being used.
    - âœ… To use the returned value, you can store it in a variable or display it.

            <p id="demo1"></p>
            <script>
                function sayHello() {
                    return "Hello User";
                }
                let message = sayHello();
                document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = message;
            </script>

            or,

            <p id="demo1"></p>
            <script>
                function sayHello() {
                    return "Hello User";
                }
                document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = sayHello();
            </script>


#) Calling a Function Many Times:
    - You can call the same function whenever you need it.

            function sayHello() {
                return "Hello World";
            }

            let a = sayHello();
            let b = sayHello();
            let c = sayHello();


#) Functions are Invoked with ():
    - ðŸ’¡ THE () OPERATOR INVOKES A FUNCTION.

            // Convert Fahrenheit to Celsius:
            function toCelsius(fahrenheit) {
                return (5/9) * (fahrenheit-32);
            }

            // Call the toCelcius() function
            let value = toCelsius(77);
    
    - âš ï¸ ACCESSING THE FUNCTION WITHOUT (), RETURNS THE FUNCTION ITSELF AND NOT THE RESULT.

            let result = toCelcius;
            document.getElementById("demo3").innerHTML = result;

            o/p: function toCelsius(farenheit) { return (5/9) * (farenheit-32); }


#) Calling vs Referencing a Function:
    - sayHello refers to the function itself. It returns the function.
    - sayHello() refers to the function result. It returns the result


#) Functions Can Be Called from Anywhere:
    - You can call functions from other functions, from events, or from any code block.
        eg: Calling a function from another function =>

            // function 1
            function greeting() {               
                return "Hello Saiyan.";
            }

            // function 2: calling function 1 from function 2
            function showGreeting() {
                document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = greeting();    // calling
            }

            showGreeting(); // calling function 2
        

        eg: Calling a function from event =>

            // invoking function 2 by button clicking event
            <button onclick="displayGreeting()">Click me!</button>
            <script>
                // function 1
                function greeting() {               
                    return "Hello Saiyan.";
                }

                // function 2: calling function 1 from function 2
                function showGreeting() {
                    document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = greeting();    // calling
                }
            </script>
            

#) Common Mistakes:
    - Expecting Return = Some functions does not return a value.
    - Expecting Output = If a function returns a value, but you must display it to see it.